Welcome to www.saucissons.com.au
The idea of Saucissons Australia was born in 2007 as it was possible to find any kind of French food products in Australia BUT nothing like we French could call saucisson.
Saucisson is one of the most popular food products in France, that’s the typical French snack, the king of picnic and apéro, saucisson is in every home.
Every year nearly 100.000 tonnes are produced in France.
The word saucisson is mentioned for the first time in 1546 in a book of the French writer Rabelais. It belongs to a type of charcuterie named as salaison (salted, fermented and air dried).
Traditionally, every farm in the countryside used to make their own saucisson in wintertime when they were killing the pig; a lot of farms still do it. It is a way to store meat for the rest of the year.
 
‘’Dans le cochon, tout est bon’’.

Bienvenue sur www.saucissons.com.au !

Cette partie du site est en francais.

Saucisson is one of the most important elements of the French culture, such as bread, wine, and cheese. As far as I remember, we always had some saucisson at home since I was a child; this is the way we, French, are brought up, no matter what part of France you are from. The perfect match: some saucisson on a wood chopping board, some bread and a glass of wine. Et voila! The curse of happiness has never been simpler. And this is the way it has always been. Traditionally, every farm in the countryside used to make its own production in wintertime for the year to come. Pork meat, minced, seasoned and stuffed into natural casing. We let the saucissons aging for many weeks, slowly, until they will be ready. Then you can easily keep them much longer, depending on the temperature, humidity, and the way you will store them; but a real saucisson doesn’t last that long, as you can’t resist: fifteen minutes is the average lifetime for a good one. It’s all about sharing, culture, and happiness.

Bon appétit!

The viande des Grisons is a speciality from the Alps, that could be described as a beef prosciutto, cured and air dried. It is the traditional meat for the raclette and fondue. Much leaner than prosciutto, des Grisons is also very good as a snack or in a sandwich, or as an entree with sliced melon or fresh fruits.

Low in fat and carbohydrates, des Grisons meat is easy to digest. It is a good source of protein and vitamin B complex. The extent of water loss during the salting and drying processes, whereby the product loses approximately half of its initial weight, is sufficient to confer excellent keeping qualities and a high nutritional value. Des Grisons meat is easy to digest. It is a good source of protein and vitamin B complex.

La viande des Grisons est une salaison de viande de bœuf des alpages, séchée et élaborée a partir d’épices et d’herbes des Alpes. Elle est généralement servie en tranches fines, le plus souvent avec la raclette. La viande des Grisons a des origines anciennes, elle était fabriquée comme provisions pour l'hiver. Le séchage de la viande permettait en effet la conservation d'une viande à haute valeur nutritive. La viande des Grisons était aussi un mets consommé lors de repas de fêtes. La fabrication de la viande des Grisons comprend trois douzaines de phases de travail au cours desquelles la viande de bœuf perd environ la moitié de son poids initial.

Semi-cooked duck foie gras from South West of France.

South West of France is the land of the "French Paradox". It refers to the low rate of coronary heart disease (CHT) in France, and especially in this region where the inhabitants, large consumers of goose and duck, are among the lowest mortality and coronary heart better life expectancy. This products have a high content of polyunsaturated fatty acids and oleic acids, protectors of the body.

The duck breed is the Mulard duck. Foie gras has been poached at the low temperature to match AQIS requirements. You can either consume as it is or either pan fry. It doesn't break, nor shrink and you don't loose much fat within the cooking.

Foie Gras Quenelles with Yabbie Coulis
 
Chef: Tristan Lanceley
 
Restaurant: Number One
 
Blend together and then add the cream and foie gras, blended into a cream into the chicken puree. Taste for salt. pass through a fine sieve, add extra salt and chilli.
One bunch of leeks, chopped and cooked in butter, then pureed.
Fill a large deep saute pane with salted water and heat until nearly boiling. Shape the quenelles with a spoon and poach for five minutes in the hot water. Remove with a slotted spoon. Place a little leek purce in the center of each plate. Place the hot quenelle in the center and nap with the yabbie coulis.
 
Yabbie Coulis
  • 200g live yabbies or marron blanched and roughly chopped
  • Mirepoix: 1 cup of 1cm dice onion, carrot, celery.
  • 2 cloves garlic
  • 2 tbsp butter or olive oil
  • Thyme bay leaf chopped
  • 500g tomato chopped
  • 500ml white wine
  • 200ml cream
  • Salt, pepper, and a tiny bit of cayenne pepper
  • Robot coupe / magimix
  • Whisk
  • Fine sieves
  • 200cm sauteuse
  • Slotted spoon
  • Absorbent paper
Gently saute the yabbie with the mirepoix and garlic until it begins to colour, add the white wine and seasoning and reduce half. Ad the chopped tomato and cook until soft.
Reduce and adjust the seasoning with salt and cayenne pepper.
Enjoy!
 
Recipe courtesy of Number One Bar

Duck Liver with Prune Jam
 
Chef: Troy Spencer
 
Restaurant: L'Etoile
 
Make a reduction with Port, Shallots, Garlic & a sprig of Thyme.
Reduce to a syrup.
Seal off Livers, place in the robot coupe, and blitz. Add reduction, followed by the melted butter then the eggs. Push through fine sieve and place in double lined terrine moulds. Place sliced or chopped Foie Gras pieces in the liver mix.

 
Place terrines in water bath and cook to it reaches 64c.
Ingredients
  • 200g of Foie Gras
  • 500g of Duck
  • 3 Shallots
  • 3 Cloves of Garlic
  • 500g Melted Butter
  • 6 Whole Eggs
  • 250ml Port
 
Recipe courtesy of L'Etoile
